answers.body_markdown:
onDismiss is a lifecycle method of DialogFragment. You are not supposed to call it.&lt;br&gt;
You have 2 options, 

**Try to use the [OnDismissListener][1]:**

```Java
dialogFragment.getDialog().setOnDismissListener(new DialogInterface.OnDismissListener() {
    @Override
    public void onDismiss(DialogInterface dialogInterface) {
        currentIndex++;
        nextWordOrTryAgain();
        updateTextView();
    }
}
```

**Or to Create a custom listener interface:**

```Java
public interface DialogDismissed {
    void onDialogDismissed();
}
```

Inside you dialog, have a setter and keep the listener interface:

```Java
public void setListener(DialogDismissed listener) {
    mListener = listener;
}
```

When you call **dismiss()** inside you dialog use:
```Java
if (mListener != null) {
    mListener.onDialogDismissed()
}
```

And when creating the Dialog, set the listener:
```Java
dialogFragment.setListener(new DialogDismissed {
    @Override
    void onDialogDismissed() {
        currentIndex++;
        nextWordOrTryAgain();
        updateTextView();
    }
});
```

  [1]: https://developer.android.com/reference/android/content/DialogInterface.OnDismissListener

