We found out that all the standard ways of getting the total memory of the current process have some issues.

* **`Runtime.getRuntime().totalMemory()`**: returns JVM memory only
* **`ActivityManager.getMemoryInfo()`**, **`Process.getFreeMemory()`** and anything else based on **`/proc/meminfo`** - returns memory info about all the processes combined (e.g. [android_util_Process.cpp](https://android.googlesource.com/platform/frameworks/base/+/master/core/jni/android_util_Process.cpp))
* **`Debug.getNativeHeapAllocatedSize()`** - uses `mallinfo()` which return information about memory allocations performed by `malloc()` and related functions only (see [android_os_Debug.cpp](https://android.googlesource.com/platform/frameworks/base/+/master/core/jni/android_os_Debug.cpp))
* **`Debug.getMemoryInfo()`** - does the job but it&#39;s too slow. It takes about **200ms** on **Nexus 6** for a single call. The performance overhead makes this function useless for us as we call it regularly and every call is quite noticeable (see [android_os_Debug.cpp](https://android.googlesource.com/platform/frameworks/base/+/master/core/jni/android_os_Debug.cpp))
* **`ActivityManager.getProcessMemoryInfo(int[])`** - calls `Debug.getMemoryInfo()` internally (see [ActivityManagerService.java](https://android.googlesource.com/platform/frameworks/base/+/master/services/core/java/com/android/server/am/ActivityManagerService.java))


